{
  "doc_id": "15843",
  "text": "COX2 is an inducible enzyme not detected in normal epithelium. Its expression is induced within a few hours of exposure to invasive organisms or pro-inflammatory cytokines including interleukin 1 and tumor necrosis factor alpha and is usually lost within 24 hours. Many of these events involve the NFK-B signaling pathway [CITATION_1] . In areas of active inflammation due to IBD, COX2 enzyme can be detected in apical epithelial cells of the inflamed mucosa [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The expression of COX2 in the small intestinal and colonic mucosa was found to be higher in experimental colitis, to correlate with inflammatory activity in IBD and to have a beneficial effect on healing in experimental colitis [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The exact mechanism by which COX2 inhibitors induced relapse in IBD is uncertain. Several hypotheses have been suggested including delayed wound healing with increased vascular permeability, maintenance of intestinal mucosa integrity and anti-inflammatory properties in intestinal tissue during inflammation [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Figure 1 . The potential pathogenesis of NSAIDS induced GI toxicity [CITATION_8] . Adapted with permission from the publisher. ",
